posts.raw_content:
As headlines tout breakthroughs at Ivy League institutions and billion-dollar endowments continue to grow, much of America remains blind to the decaying foundation beneath its community colleges where the majority of students actually study. St. Petersburg College (SPC) in Florida is one such institution where the daily realities paint a far different picture than the glossy brochures or national rankings might suggest.

Here, education often plays second fiddle to survival both financial and academic. Students, many of whom work full-time jobs or raise families, log into group discussions that have been gutted of meaning. What should be collaboration quickly deteriorates into copy-paste sessions of ChatGPT outputs, repackaged as critical thought.

Foreign exchange students whom institutions are financially incentivized to enroll frequently flaunt their use of AI tools, often without consequence. It’s an open secret. A wink. A shrug. A policy, somewhere, left unread.

Meanwhile, academic dishonesty is no longer a hidden shame it’s a survival skill. The rules are inconsistent, the enforcement subjective, and faculty? Often powerless or disinterested.

Even outside the classroom, the absurdity continues.

My company, Murder Mittens—yes, that's the name—recently received a warning email from an SPC department about appearing “scary.” Apparently, our branding offended someone’s delicate sensibilities. One wonders if they’ve ever heard of Liquid Death, a multimillion-dollar water brand whose entire existence revolves around edgy satire and metal-inspired marketing. But that brand is sold in Whole Foods. Ours? Too scary.

The bigger point? Misplaced priorities.

St. Petersburg College—and many schools like it—struggle with basic operational competence. Billing errors. Delayed textbooks. Missing credits for military service. Little transparency. Even less accountability. And a lot of pretending.

If this is the foundation of America’s “accessible” higher education system, what happens when it crumbles?

It’s easy to point to Harvard, Yale, or Stanford as pinnacles of our system. But they serve a fraction of the population. The rest of us? We navigate campuses where “discussion” means rewording AI outputs, where cheating is normalized, and where the system gaslights students into believing their failure is personal, not structural.

If education is supposed to be the great equalizer, then community colleges must be the battleground—not the afterthought.

Tim Norwood
